  "local_port": 49476,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the difference between FRS, PRD, TRD, SRS, MRD, BRD?",
  "response": "FRS, PRD, TRD, SRS, MRD, and BRD are different types of documents used in various stages of product development, software engineering, and project management. Here's a brief overview of each:\n\n### **1. FRS (Functional Requirements Specification)**\n   - **Purpose**: Defines the system's functional requirements in detail.\n   - **Content**: Describes what the system should do, including features, behavior, and interactions.\n   - **Used in**: Software development to guide developers in building the system.\n   - **Audience**: Developers, testers, and stakeholders.\n\n### **2. PRD (Product Requirements Document)**\n   - **Purpose**: Outlines the features and functionality of a product from a high-level perspective.\n   - **Content**: Includes product goals, target audience, key features, and timelines.\n   - **Used in**: Product management to align stakeholders and guide the development process.\n   - **Audience**: Product managers, designers, developers, and business stakeholders.\n\n### **3. TRD (Technical Requirements Document)**\n   - **Purpose**: Specifies the technical aspects of a system or product.\n   - **Content**: Details the hardware, software, architecture, and technical constraints.\n   - **Used in**: Engineering and development to ensure technical feasibility.\n   - **Audience**: Developers, system architects, and engineers.\n\n### **4. SRS (Software Requirements Specification)**\n   - **Purpose**: Provides a comprehensive description of the software system to be developed.\n   - **Content**: Includes functional and non-functional requirements, use cases, and system behavior.\n   - **Used in**: Software development to ensure all requirements are captured and implemented.\n   - **Audience**: Developers, testers, and project managers.\n\n### **5. MRD (Market Requirements Document)**\n   - **Purpose**: Captures market needs and customer requirements for a product.\n   - **Content**: Includes market analysis, customer pain points, competitive landscape, and business opportunities.\n   - **Used in**: Product management to align product development with market demand.\n   - **Audience**: Product managers, marketing teams, and business stakeholders.\n\n### **6. BRD (Business Requirements Document)**\n   - **Purpose**: Defines the business needs and objectives for a project or product.\n   - **Content**: Includes business goals, stakeholder requirements, and high-level business processes.\n   - **Used in**: Project management to ensure the solution aligns with business objectives.\n   - **Audience**: Business analysts, stakeholders, and project managers.\n\n### **Key Differences**\n- **Focus**: PRD, MRD, and BRD focus on business and market needs, while FRS, SRS, and TRD focus on technical and functional details.\n- **Audience**: Business stakeholders and product managers typically use PRD, MRD, and BRD, whereas developers and engineers use FRS, SRS, and TRD.\n- **Level of Detail**: BRD and MRD are high-level, while FRS, SRS, and TRD are more detailed and technical.\n\nThese documents often work together to ensure that a product or project meets both business and technical requirements.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
